    "body": "Sorry if this out of scope of ur issue, but it could be related since I was thinking is the Ethereum susceptible to a similar hash collision attack as the onedescribed in the Utreexo 2019 original paper ...\r\nIf the attacker in a position to know all the Trie leaves then the complexity of faking one reduces by the number of leaves. For example for a 256bit hash and say 2³² leaves it reduces  from 2²⁵⁶ to 2²²⁴. \r\n![IMG_20210430_203147](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/83260375/116742864-4afcd800-a9f8-11eb-8fb6-80dce950ab46.jpg)\r\nHe solves this by concatenating the block hash (and suggests position but that's another story)\r\n![IMG_20210430_203553](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/83260375/116742947-797ab300-a9f8-11eb-9453-2a4d9370955e.jpg)\r\n.\r\nNow I was thinking does concatenating the key hash in EIP-3102 have the same effect?\r\nhttps://eips.ethereum.org/EIPS/eip-3102\r\nWhere it is stated that\r\nleaf_hash = hash(hash(key) || hash(leaf_value))\r\nIs \"key\" here an address or what?and how many bits?\r\nThat's what is written there...\r\n![IMG_20210429_202939](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/83260375/116743229-eb52fc80-a9f8-11eb-8854-c4fdcf4e8764.jpg)\r\n.\r\nHope my thought is in the scope of ur issue.\r\n",
